      <exercise id="fs-id1169737814645" type="problems-exercises">
        <problem id="fs-id1169737814648">  
      <para xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0" id="import-auto-id1169737966585">In a very mild winter climate, a heat pump has heat transfer from an environment at <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>5</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>00</m:mtext><m:mtext>º</m:mtext><m:mtext>C</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{5 "." "00"°C} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> to one at <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>35</m:mtext><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mn>0</m:mn><m:mtext>º</m:mtext><m:mtext>C</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{"35" "." 0°C} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. What is the best possible coefficient of performance for these temperatures? Explicitly show how you follow the steps in the <link target-id="fs-id1169738116696">Problem-Solving Strategies for Thermodynamics</link>.</para></problem></exercise>
      
